## Context

### Background

The web UI is fully functional and mobile-optimized (post mobile ADR). The desktop experience
is correct but does not yet leverage the desktop's surface area for discoverable, efficient
browsing. Specific gaps:

- **No date-based filtering.** Users cannot narrow results to "photos from last June" or
  "everything I took on a specific day." The only filters are text query, tag, and path.
  `taken_at` data is stored and grouped in the UI but never filterable.
- **Grid density is fixed.** The `TARGET_ROW_HEIGHT = 220` constant is hardcoded. Power users
  with large libraries want to see more thumbnails at once; users reviewing for selection want
  to see fewer, larger images.
- **Lightbox metadata is static.** The date in the Details panel is plain text. Clicking it
  to pivot to "all photos from this day" is an obvious action that is impossible today.
- **Library switching requires navigating away.** To move from Library A to Library B the user
  must return to `/` (Libraries page), find Library B, and click Browse. There is no in-context
  shortcut.
- **No keyboard shortcut discoverability.** Arrow-key navigation and Escape work in the
  lightbox, but there is no hint or reference. Users who do not discover them miss out.

### What is NOT in scope

- Dark/light mode toggle — always dark; separate feature.
- Authentication / user management — Phase 5 of main project plan.
- Offline / PWA support.
- Native mobile apps.
- AI description editing or tag editing — separate feature request.
- WCAG full audit — date links and keyboard hints will be ARIA-labeled but a full audit is
  a separate workstream.
- Video timeline scrubbing — future feature.
- Bulk selection / bulk tag operations — future feature.

