## Design Decisions

### Date filter architecture: API extension, not client-side filtering

Filtering by date server-side is required because the browse mode uses cursor-based infinite
scroll — the full dataset is never in memory simultaneously. Client-side filtering of an
infinite scroll would silently omit matching assets beyond the loaded window.

The minimal backend change: add `date_from` and `date_to` (ISO 8601 date strings, `YYYY-MM-DD`)
as optional query parameters to `GET /v1/search`. The backend applies an inclusive range filter
on `taken_at` (falling back to `file_mtime` for assets with no EXIF date).

When a date filter is active in the UI, the browse mode switches to **search mode** (using
`searchAssets`) even when the text query is empty. This reuses the existing dual-mode
architecture without adding date filtering to the cursor-based page endpoint. The tradeoff is
that date-filtered results do not support infinite scroll (they return up to the search limit),
which is acceptable because a typical single-day result set is bounded.

URL representation: `?date_from=2024-06-04&date_to=2024-06-04` (single day), or a range.
These compose additively with existing `?q=&tag=&path=` params.

### Grid zoom: single slider controls `TARGET_ROW_HEIGHT` / `MIN_CELL_WIDTH`

A single zoom slider (5 notches: XS → XL) maps to specific `TARGET_ROW_HEIGHT` values for
the justified desktop layout. On narrow screens (≤700px fixed-grid mode) the same slider maps
to `MIN_CELL_WIDTH` breakpoints. One control works for both layout modes.

Zoom level is persisted to `localStorage` as `lv_grid_zoom` (default: level 3 = 220px, current
hardcoded value). This is a user preference, not a URL param — it does not affect shareable
links.

### Lightbox date click: URL navigation with preserved filters

Clicking `taken_at` in the Lightbox navigates to the current URL with `date_from` and
`date_to` set to the asset's date (time stripped, date only), then closes the lightbox. This
preserves all other URL params (`q`, `tag`, `path`, `libraryId`) so the "scope" of the library
and any active path or tag filters are maintained. The result: the user lands back in the grid
view, filtered to that one day, still inside the same library and folder context.

### Library quick-switcher: `⌘K` / `Ctrl+K` command palette

A modal command palette (similar to VS Code's file switcher or Spotlight) provides the fastest
path to switch libraries without navigating to the Libraries page. It renders a search-filtered
list of all libraries. Selecting one navigates to `/libraries/:id/browse`. The palette is
dismissed by Escape, backdrop click, or successful navigation.

