## Phase 1 — Date Search

**Goal**: Users can filter the media grid by a date or date range. Clicking the photo date in
the Lightbox applies a single-day date filter instantly.

### 1a — Backend: API date parameters

**File**: `src/lumiverb/api/routers/search.py` (or equivalent search endpoint)

Add two optional query params to `GET /v1/search`:

```python
date_from: str | None = Query(None, description="ISO date YYYY-MM-DD, inclusive lower bound on taken_at / file_mtime")
date_to: str | None = Query(None, description="ISO date YYYY-MM-DD, inclusive upper bound")
```

Filter logic (SQLModel / SQLAlchemy):

```python
if date_from:
    dt_from = datetime.strptime(date_from, "%Y-%m-%d").replace(tzinfo=timezone.utc)
    # Use taken_at if available, fall back to file_mtime
    query = query.filter(
        func.coalesce(Asset.taken_at, Asset.file_mtime) >= dt_from
    )
if date_to:
    dt_to = datetime.strptime(date_to, "%Y-%m-%d").replace(tzinfo=timezone.utc) \
            + timedelta(days=1)  # exclusive upper bound (end of day)
    query = query.filter(
        func.coalesce(Asset.taken_at, Asset.file_mtime) < dt_to
    )
```

The existing Quickwit full-text search layer is unchanged — date filtering is applied as a
post-filter on the SQL result set (the search route already hydrates results from the DB after
Quickwit returns matching asset IDs).

### 1b — API client

**File**: `src/ui/web/src/api/types.ts`

Extend `SearchParams`:

```typescript
export interface SearchParams {
  libraryId: string;
  q: string;
  pathPrefix?: string;
  tag?: string;
  dateFrom?: string;  // YYYY-MM-DD
  dateTo?: string;    // YYYY-MM-DD
  limit?: number;
  offset?: number;
}
```

**File**: `src/ui/web/src/api/client.ts`

Pass new params in `searchAssets`:

```typescript
export async function searchAssets(params: SearchParams): Promise<SearchResponse> {
  const url = new URL(`/v1/libraries/${params.libraryId}/search`, window.location.origin);
  if (params.q) url.searchParams.set("q", params.q);
  if (params.pathPrefix) url.searchParams.set("path_prefix", params.pathPrefix);
  if (params.tag) url.searchParams.set("tag", params.tag);
  if (params.dateFrom) url.searchParams.set("date_from", params.dateFrom);
  if (params.dateTo) url.searchParams.set("date_to", params.dateTo);
  if (params.limit) url.searchParams.set("limit", String(params.limit));
  // ...fetch
}
```

### 1c — FilterBar: date filter UI

**File**: `src/ui/web/src/components/FilterBar.tsx`

Add a date filter section between the search input and the chiclets. It is collapsed by
default (shows only a calendar icon button). Clicking the button expands a row of preset
chips and, optionally, a custom range:

**Structure:**

```
[🔍 Search input          ] [📅]      ← calendar button toggles date filter row
─────────────────────────────────────
[Today] [Yesterday] [This week] [This month] [This year] [Custom ▸]
─────────────────────────────────────
Active chiclets: [🔍 landscape ×] [📅 Jun 4, 2024 ×]
```

**Preset definitions** (computed at render time, no external date library needed):

```typescript
function getDatePresets(): DatePreset[] {
  const today = new Date();
  const fmt = (d: Date) => d.toISOString().slice(0, 10); // YYYY-MM-DD
  const startOf = (d: Date) => new Date(d.getFullYear(), d.getMonth(), d.getDate());

  const todayStr = fmt(startOf(today));
  const yday = new Date(today); yday.setDate(today.getDate() - 1);
  const weekStart = new Date(today); weekStart.setDate(today.getDate() - today.getDay());
  const monthStart = new Date(today.getFullYear(), today.getMonth(), 1);
  const yearStart = new Date(today.getFullYear(), 0, 1);

  return [
    { label: "Today",      from: todayStr,          to: todayStr },
    { label: "Yesterday",  from: fmt(startOf(yday)), to: fmt(startOf(yday)) },
    { label: "This week",  from: fmt(weekStart),     to: todayStr },
    { label: "This month", from: fmt(monthStart),    to: todayStr },
    { label: "This year",  from: fmt(yearStart),     to: todayStr },
  ];
}
```

**Custom range:** Clicking "Custom ▸" expands two native `<input type="date">` fields
(from / to). No third-party date picker library. Apply button sets the URL params.

**Chiclet display logic:**

```typescript
function formatDateChiclet(from: string, to: string): string {
  if (from === to) {
    return new Date(from + "T00:00:00").toLocaleDateString("en-US", {
      month: "short", day: "numeric", year: "numeric",
    }); // "Jun 4, 2024"
  }
  // same month: "Jun 1 – 30, 2024"
  // different month/year: "Jun 1, 2024 – Mar 22, 2026"
  // ...abbreviated range
}
```

**URL param contract:**
- `?date_from=YYYY-MM-DD` and `?date_to=YYYY-MM-DD` always appear together.
- Removing the chiclet removes both params.

**FilterBar state additions:**

```typescript
const [searchParams, setSearchParams] = useSearchParams();
const dateFrom = searchParams.get("date_from") ?? undefined;
const dateTo   = searchParams.get("date_to")   ?? undefined;
const [showDateRow, setShowDateRow] = useState(Boolean(dateFrom));
```

Calendar icon button shows an indigo dot indicator when a date filter is active.

### 1d — BrowsePage: activate search mode when date filter is set

**File**: `src/ui/web/src/pages/BrowsePage.tsx`

Add `dateFrom` and `dateTo` to the URL param reads (alongside existing `q`, `tag`, `path`):

```typescript
const dateFrom = searchParams.get("date_from") ?? undefined;
const dateTo   = searchParams.get("date_to")   ?? undefined;
```

Change the condition that selects browse mode vs search mode:

```typescript
// Before
const isSearchMode = Boolean(activeQ);

// After
const isSearchMode = Boolean(activeQ || dateFrom);
```

Pass date params to `searchAssets`:

```typescript
const searchResult = useQuery({
  queryKey: ["search", libraryId, activeQ, activeTag, pathPrefix, dateFrom, dateTo],
  queryFn: () => searchAssets({
    libraryId: libraryId!,
    q: activeQ ?? "",
    pathPrefix,
    tag: activeTag,
    dateFrom,
    dateTo,
    limit: 500,
  }),
  enabled: isSearchMode && Boolean(libraryId),
});
```

The `limit: 500` ceiling is appropriate for single-day date filter results. For wide date
ranges (e.g., "This year") results are capped at 500 with a `"Showing first 500 results —
narrow your search to see more"` banner when `total > 500`.

