## Phase 4 — Library Quick-Switcher & Keyboard Reference

**Goal**: Power users can switch libraries and discover keyboard shortcuts without navigating
away from their current context.

### 4a — Command palette (`⌘K` / `Ctrl+K`)

#### `src/ui/web/src/components/CommandPalette.tsx` — Create

A modal that appears over the current page. It fetches the library list and renders a
search-filtered list of libraries. Keyboard-navigable (↑/↓ arrows, Enter to select, Esc to
dismiss).

```typescript
interface CommandPaletteProps {
  open: boolean;
  onClose: () => void;
}
```

**Structure:**

```tsx
// Full-screen backdrop
<div className="fixed inset-0 z-50 flex items-start justify-center pt-24 px-4"
     onClick={onClose}>

  {/* Palette panel — stops propagation so clicks inside don't close */}
  <div className="w-full max-w-lg rounded-xl bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700
                  shadow-2xl overflow-hidden"
       onClick={e => e.stopPropagation()}>

    {/* Search input */}
    <div className="flex items-center gap-3 px-4 py-3 border-b border-gray-800">
      <MagnifyingGlassIcon className="h-4 w-4 text-gray-500 shrink-0" />
      <input
        ref={inputRef}
        autoFocus
        placeholder="Go to library…"
        className="flex-1 bg-transparent text-sm text-gray-100 placeholder-gray-500
                   outline-none"
        value={query}
        onChange={e => setQuery(e.target.value)}
      />
      <kbd className="text-xs text-gray-600 font-mono">Esc</kbd>
    </div>

    {/* Results list */}
    <ul className="max-h-72 overflow-y-auto py-2">
      {filtered.map((lib, i) => (
        <li key={lib.library_id}>
          <button
            className={`w-full text-left px-4 py-2.5 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm
              ${i === activeIndex
                ? "bg-indigo-600/30 text-indigo-300"
                : "text-gray-300 hover:bg-gray-800"}`}
            onClick={() => selectLibrary(lib)}
          >
            <BookOpenIcon className="h-4 w-4 text-gray-500 shrink-0" />
            <span className="flex-1 truncate">{lib.name}</span>
            <Badge status={lib.scan_status} />
          </button>
        </li>
      ))}
      {filtered.length === 0 && (
        <li className="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-gray-500">No libraries match "{query}"</li>
      )}
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>
```

**Navigation logic:**

```typescript
// Keyboard handler on the input
onKeyDown: (e) => {
  if (e.key === "ArrowDown") { setActiveIndex(i => Math.min(i + 1, filtered.length - 1)); }
  if (e.key === "ArrowUp")   { setActiveIndex(i => Math.max(i - 1, 0)); }
  if (e.key === "Enter")     { selectLibrary(filtered[activeIndex]); }
  if (e.key === "Escape")    { onClose(); }
}
```

`selectLibrary` navigates to `/libraries/${lib.library_id}/browse` and calls `onClose`.

**Filtering:** case-insensitive substring match on `lib.name`. No fuzzy matching (simple and
predictable).

#### `src/ui/web/src/components/AppShell.tsx` — Modify

Add `CommandPalette` state and global keyboard listener:

```typescript
const [paletteOpen, setPaletteOpen] = useState(false);

useEffect(() => {
  const handler = (e: KeyboardEvent) => {
    if ((e.metaKey || e.ctrlKey) && e.key === "k") {
      e.preventDefault();
      setPaletteOpen(o => !o);
    }
  };
  document.addEventListener("keydown", handler);
  return () => document.removeEventListener("keydown", handler);
}, []);
```

Render `<CommandPalette open={paletteOpen} onClose={() => setPaletteOpen(false)} />` at the
end of the AppShell return, outside the main scroll area so it overlays everything.

Add a trigger button in the Sidebar header area (desktop) for discoverability:

```tsx
<button
  onClick={() => setPaletteOpen(true)}
  className="hidden md:flex w-full items-center gap-2 px-3 py-2 rounded-lg
             text-xs text-gray-500 bg-gray-800/50 hover:bg-gray-800
             border border-gray-700/50 transition-colors"
  aria-label="Open library switcher"
>
  <MagnifyingGlassIcon className="h-3.5 w-3.5 shrink-0" />
  <span className="flex-1 text-left">Go to library</span>
  <kbd className="font-mono text-[10px] text-gray-600">⌘K</kbd>
</button>
```

This button sits at the top of the Sidebar (above the library list), visible only on desktop.
On mobile the Sidebar is hidden and `⌘K` still works globally via the `useEffect`.

### 4b — Keyboard shortcuts reference modal

#### `src/ui/web/src/components/KeyboardShortcuts.tsx` — Create

A modal listing all keyboard shortcuts, triggered by pressing `?` from any non-input context.

```typescript
const SHORTCUT_GROUPS = [
  {
    label: "Navigation",
    shortcuts: [
      { keys: ["⌘", "K"], description: "Open library switcher" },
      { keys: ["?"], description: "Show / hide this panel" },
    ],
  },
  {
    label: "Lightbox",
    shortcuts: [
      { keys: ["←", "→"], description: "Previous / next photo" },
      { keys: ["Esc"], description: "Close lightbox" },
      { keys: ["F"], description: "Toggle fullscreen" },
      { keys: ["Space"], description: "Start / stop slideshow" },
    ],
  },
] as const;
```

Rendered as a standard `<Modal>` (reuses existing Modal component). The `?` shortcut is
registered in `AppShell` (not in Lightbox — Lightbox already has its own `?` handler for the
hint overlay, and both independently manage their own state).

**AppShell `?` handler** (global, not inside a text input):

```typescript
const handler = (e: KeyboardEvent) => {
  if (e.key === "?" && !isInputFocused()) {
    setShortcutsOpen(o => !o);
  }
};

function isInputFocused(): boolean {
  const tag = document.activeElement?.tagName;
  return tag === "INPUT" || tag === "TEXTAREA" || tag === "SELECT";
}
```

### 4c — Sidebar "active library" context

**File**: `src/ui/web/src/components/Sidebar.tsx`

Currently, when browsing a library, the sidebar shows the library's DirectoryTree but there is
no visible indication of which library is active (the name appears in the breadcrumb, not the
sidebar). Add a library name header in the sidebar, visible when `libraryId` is set:

```tsx
{libraryId && libraryName && (
  <div className="px-3 py-2 border-b border-gray-800">
    <p className="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider mb-0.5">Library</p>
    <p className="text-sm font-medium text-gray-200 truncate" title={libraryName}>
      {libraryName}
    </p>
  </div>
)}
```

`libraryName` is passed as a new prop to Sidebar from AppShell, where it can be derived from
the current route params and the cached library list query.

**AppShell** passes `libraryName` to Sidebar:

```typescript
// In AppShell, derive library name from queryClient cache (already fetched by LibrariesPage)
const libraryName = useLibraryName(libraryId); // see below
```

```typescript
// New hook: src/ui/web/src/hooks/useLibraryName.ts
export function useLibraryName(libraryId?: string): string | undefined {
  const { data } = useQuery({
    queryKey: ["libraries"],
    queryFn: () => listLibraries(),
    staleTime: 60_000,
  });
  return data?.find(l => l.library_id === libraryId)?.name;
}
```

